Chapter 1
Cohren
4h30, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially because it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. Silently getting out of his bed, he put on his combat uniform, attached his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook attached to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: breathing apparatus, goggles, everything necessary. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly stepped out of the barracks, the sound of squelching mud and ice echoing under his boots.
He pulled a lighter from the pocket of his vest and a cigarette from the other. As he lit it, he took a small puff before opening the door slowly. Last week, he had had to be creative to wake the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the pre-set alarm clock; half the time, it didn't work, as what came out of the speakers was just a faint whistling sound.
"Do you wake them up?" Cohren turned to see Second Lieutenant Nemic approach.
"Ouch," replied Cohren.
"What are you planning to use this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers rushed out, already dressed and equipped.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What woke you up?" asked Cohren.
"Well, first of all, we didn't want to see what you had planned for us to wake up today. Second, the first shock troops to stand up are the first at breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You make a point, Specialist," said Cohren. He extended his hand and activated a switch. A loud alarm sounded inside the barracks, strong and shrill. He heard commotion inside and agitation.
"For crying out loud, Valturi," exclaimed Nemic. "One would think they would have learned to wake up as early as you after all this time."
"Well, my training camp buddies here did," said Cohren, turning towards Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But, once again, their squad and section leaders know how to wake up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company poured out in masses. They all had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, others more irritated.
"Hello everyone," said Cohren cheerfully.
"Excuse me, sir, why do you insist on waking us up like this?" asked one of the shock troop squad members, a corporal.
"Because standard alarms are crap. And because Daybreak doesn't hit the snooze button," replied Cohren.
"Make sure you have all your personal effects," he continued. As first lieutenant and the commanding officer's assistant, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company alongside the company captain, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be returning. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to perform final checks and gather rations for the day."
The members of the Exodus company dispersed. They were part of the second division of the shock troops, second army. Initially, they were split into two separate companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. This was a splintered company, and Cohren wasn't sure what to think about his promotion to first lieutenant, primarily due to the reasons that motivated it.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked together under the light of the many floodlights of the forward operational base, powered by generators. Most were tinted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild Weasel assaults, both in the air and on the ground, to combat them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," began Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"An advance operational base outside Ianlos. We've been sent to support the land assault," replied Cohren, pulling on his cigarette. A part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to tobacco, but a year of combat changes a man, and he fell silent.
"Shit. The situation is deteriorating on the front," grumbled Nemic. "All the news coming from here is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan front.' Why not send help to the Howland front?"
"Amen, brother," said Cohren, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "Anyhow, we're going with the first armored platoon, so we won't have to walk. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Shaw gave us a ride?" asked Nemic, somewhat surprised.
"Yeah. Honestly, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable."
Cohren put his thumb and index finger to his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "All units of Exodus Company, assemble at the west vehicle park once you're done. We leave with the first armored platoon at 5 AM."
Every few seconds, he received responses from squadron leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were all low-ranking sergeants when they arrived here. All four had been very good friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed so long ago, even if it couldn't be more than two years. They were then squadron leaders. But Craith now commanded the second platoon since last week, after the demobilization of the previous commander, who was injured by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked toward the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of about eight Kronos main battle tanks and four Strykers. Their crews were busy ensuring their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking with the armored platoon commander. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked toward them, his usually cold face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol holster before looking back again. "I suppose the company is ready."
